Write a JavaScript function `flattenObject(obj)` that flattens a nested object into a single-level object with dot-notation keys.

Include this test code at the end:

const result = flattenObject({ a: { b: { c: 1 } }, d: 2, e: { f: { g: { h: 'hello' } }, i: [1, 2, 3] } });
console.log(JSON.stringify(result, null, 2));

```javascript
function flattenObject(obj, parentKey = '', result = {}) {
  for (const key in obj) {
    const newKey = parentKey ? `${parentKey}.${key}` : key;
    if (typeof obj[key] === 'object' && obj[key] !== null && !Array.isArray(obj[key])) {
      flattenObject(obj[key], newKey, result);
    } else {
      result[newKey] = obj[key];
    }
  }
  return result;
}

const result = flattenObject({ a: { b: { c: 1 } }, d: 2, e: { f: { g: { h: 'hello' } }, i: [1, 2, 3] } });
console.log(JSON.stringify(result, null, 2));
```

This function `flattenObject` recursively iterates through the object, concatenating keys with a dot notation when necessary. It avoids flattening arrays and non-object values. The test code demonstrates its functionality by flattening a nested object and logging the result in a formatted JSON string.

Write a JavaScript function `groupBy(arr, keyFn)` that groups array elements by the return value of `keyFn`. Returns an object where keys are the group names and values are arrays of elements.

Include this test code at the end:

const people = [
  { name: 'Alice', age: 25 },
  { name: 'Bob', age: 30 },
  { name: 'Charlie', age: 25 },
  { name: 'Diana', age: 30 },
  { name: 'Eve', age: 35 }
];

const byAge = groupBy(people, p => p.age);
console.log(JSON.stringify(byAge));

const words = ['hello', 'hi', 'world', 'hey', 'wonder'];
const byFirst = groupBy(words, w => w[0]);
console.log(JSON.stringify(byFirst));

```javascript
function groupBy(arr, keyFn) {
  const result = {};
  arr.forEach(item => {
    const key = keyFn(item);
    if (!result[key]) {
      result[key] = [];
    }
    result[key].push(item);
  });
  return result;
}

// Test code
const people = [
  { name: 'Alice', age: 25 },
  { name: 'Bob', age: 30 },
  { name: 'Charlie', age: 25 },
  { name: 'Diana', age: 30 },
  { name: 'Eve', age: 35 }
];

const byAge = groupBy(people, p => p.age);
console.log(JSON.stringify(byAge));

const words = ['hello', 'hi', 'world', 'hey', 'wonder'];
const byFirst = groupBy(words, w => w[0]);
console.log(JSON.stringify(byFirst));
```

This function `groupBy` takes an array and a key function as arguments. It iterates over the array, computes the key for each element using the provided key function, and groups elements into arrays based on these keys in an object. The test code demonstrates grouping people by age and words by their first letter.
